Feb 18 2009 	Perfect case of style over function in some ways	I stayed at the Intercontinental Dubai Festival City for 2 nights on business at the end of January 2009. I was upgraded from single to double on arrival. The receptionist was very friendly but seemed very jumpy, and her English wasn't as good as you might expect for a front desk position in a major hotel chain, but we muddled through. An example of her slightly scatty approach was that I had to ask where the elevators where to the room, as she seemed to totally forget I might want to know that. As I found out, the elevators are round 2 corners, so they are not visible from the front desk. Also, unusually, I was not escorted to my room and had nobody to show me its features, something that is standard in all reasonable hotels these days? My bags arrived quickly though.The hotel itself has only been open a matter of months, so as you would expect it is visually impressive. The lobby is spacious with lots of marble, and there were some very uncomfortable but very trendy chairs. The whole hotel concept is very modern, and the room was no different. The decor had a brown/cream/white motif, with lots of plastics and man-made materials. It felt a bit like being in an Ikea showroom.I was left with the distinct feeling that the designers had tried a bit too hard to be modern and trendy, with style seemingly overcoming function across the whole room.The bathroom is split into 3 distinct sections. On the left behind a frosted glass door is the toilet and bidet. Centre is the sink. On the right behind a clear glass door and wall is the bath and shower. The entrance from the bedroom area is sliding door opposite the sink. A short corridor runs from the sink area to a sliding door that opens in the very small hall area by the entrance door. The corridor featured some shelves with ornaments, and an extremely shallow wardrobe containing a bathrobe and slippers. Seemed to be a lot of wasted space there. There was a bigger and more functional wardrobe in the hall area near the desk/table.The weirdest aspect was the shower and bath area. It is a “wet room” - i.e. all tiled, with no shower cubicle or curtain. That's fine, but it struck me as pretty weird that the controls for the shower were 5 feet across the other side of the room, so if you want to adjust the water flow or temperature, you'll need to take a trip across the room out of the water flow. Even weirder was the fact that when you switched on the bath taps, the water dropped about 8 feet from the ceiling into the bath, making a considerable noise and splashing a fair amount of water about. There was tons of hot water and the bath was great, but if you are having a long soak and fancy topping up the water once you are in, you’ll need telescopic arms or you have to get out of the bath, as the taps are about 4 feet away next to the shower controls, which sort of defeats the object of having a relaxing soak. These things aren't the end of the world I acknowledge, but it just makes me think that the designers were trying just that bit too hard to be distinctive and trendy. You can achieve style along with function in my view, and when it comes to a hotel, you don‘t need or want gimmicks - just put the water controls where a normal human being wants them please!A lot of business people stay at the hotel. The “office area” was a round plastic table with a very trendy chair, and the second chair was a low plastic mushroom-shaped stool. As someone who needed to use this area, I found it pretty useless and very uncomfortable. Again, style over substance. The bed was OK though, and the flat screen TV was sensibly placed on the wall at the foot of the bed. The light system was something of a mystery for my whole stay. Figuring out which button actually operated which of the many lights and lamps in the room proved to be a case of trial and error. The hotel has a good location in Festival City, and you can access the adjacent huge shopping mall through a walkway straight from the hotel. There are plenty of restaurants and fast food joints there, plus a lot of very empty shops with overpriced luxury goods - the economic recession is certainly starting to hit Dubai.I didn’t eat at any of the hotel’s restaurants, but the bar on the ground floor was OK and there was a terrace overlooking Dubai Creek. There were a couple of pretty obvious hookers there both nights I was in the bar, and you would have thought the hotel would do a better job of keeping them out. Drinks weren‘t cheap. There is also a bar on something like the 26th floor, giving a nice view. Housekeeping was not the greatest. When I arrived the small marble table by the minibar cabinet had a sticky substance in the middle of it. It was still there on checking out 2 days later. The receptionist at checkout was efficient and pleasant.So, a decent enough place, but the designers just tried too hard and left their common sense at home on a couple of things in my opinion. I wouldn’t mind staying there again, but there are better hotels in Dubai which are probably cheaper too. One thing this place has that absolutely nobody else can compete with however is the world’s tallest doorman! The guy is immense, and the checkout receptionist told me that he used to be in the Guinness Book of World Records, and he is now the world’s 3rd tallest man.	
